import geopandas as gpd
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Assuming Bedbug_Reporting.csv is your dataset with 'Longitude' and 'Latitude' columns
Bedbug = pd.read_csv('C:/Users/meghn/OneDrive/Documents/Rprogramming/Bedbug_Reporting.csv')

# Create a GeoDataFrame with latitude and longitude
gdf = gpd.GeoDataFrame(Bedbug, geometry=gpd.points_from_xy(Bedbug['Longitude'], Bedbug['Latitude']))

# Load a GeoJSON file with the boundaries of NYC boroughs
custom = gpd.read_file('C:/Users/meghn/OneDrive/Documents/Rprogramming/geocustom.json')

# Spatial join to associate each point with a borough
gdf = gpd.sjoin(gdf, custom, op='within')

# Plotting a scatter plot
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
sns.scatterplot(data=gdf, x='Longitude', y='Latitude', hue='Borough', palette='Set1', s=50)
plt.title('Bedbug Infestations Choropleth Map')
plt.show()

import geopandas as gpd
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Assuming Bedbug_Reporting.csv is your dataset with 'Longitude' and 'Latitude' columns
Bedbug = pd.read_csv('C:/Users/meghn/OneDrive/Documents/Rprogramming/Bedbug_Reporting.csv')

# Create a GeoDataFrame with latitude and longitude
gdf = gpd.GeoDataFrame(Bedbug, geometry=gpd.points_from_xy(Bedbug['Longitude'], Bedbug['Latitude']))

# Load a GeoJSON file with the boundaries of NYC
nyc_boroughs = gpd.read_file('C:/Users/meghn/OneDrive/Documents/Rprogramming/geocustom.json')

# Spatial join to associate each point with a borough
gdf = gpd.sjoin(gdf, nyc_boroughs, op='within')

# Load a GeoJSON file with the boundaries of NYC boroughs
nyc_map = gpd.read_file('C:/Users/meghn/OneDrive/Documents/Rprogramming/Borough Boundaries.geojson')

# Plotting the NYC map
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(40, 30))
nyc_map.plot(ax=ax, color='lightgray', edgecolor='black')

# Plotting a scatter plot on top of the NYC map
scatter = sns.scatterplot(data=gdf, x='Longitude', y='Latitude', hue='Borough', palette='Set1', s=50, ax=ax)

# Set a larger title in bold and red color
scatter.set_title('Bedbug Infestations in NYC', fontsize=24, fontweight='bold', color='red')

# Move the legend to the upper right inside the plot
legend = scatter.legend(loc='upper right', bbox_to_anchor=(1.00, 1), borderaxespad=0., markerscale=0.8)

# Adjust the legend fontsize
for text in legend.get_texts():
    text.set_fontsize(14)

# Set larger axis labels
ax.set_xlabel('Longitude', fontsize=20)
ax.set_ylabel('Latitude', fontsize=20)

plt.show()
